  {
    "page": 5,
    "block_id": "page_005:block_050",
    "block_type": "text",
    "text": "CaVulner : Automated Context-Aware Identification of Vulnerable Versions 5",
    "bbox": [
      45.827999114990234,
      60.60470199584961,
      440.1680908203125,
      69.88189697265625
    ],
    "reading_order": 50,
    "column_guess": null,
    "confidence": "medium"
  },
  {
    "page": 5,
    "block_id": "page_005:block_051",
    "block_type": "text",
    "text": "for bug detection rather than vulnerabilities, it represents the best-performing variant of SZZ to date and thus provides a strong reference point for evaluating the boundaries of current methodologies. The motivating example is illustrated in Figure 1 , which examines CVE - 2018 - 1000406, an arbitrary file - write vulnerability caused by Jenkins’s failure to properly normalize and constrain user input. The correct range of affected versions for this vulnerability is [ 1 . 312 , 1 . 658 ] ∪[ 2 . 0 , 2 . 145 ] . However, all three tools report the range as [ 1 . 362 , 1 . 658 ] ∪[ 2 . 0 , 2 . 145 ] , incorrectly identifying 1.362 as the lower bound. This discrepancy indicates a shared weakness across these tools in accurately tracing back to the true inducing commit. Each tool failed for different reasons:",
    "bbox": [
      45.52899932861328,
      83.43709564208984,
      441.703857421875,
      192.84640502929688
    ],
    "reading_order": 51,
    "column_guess": null,
    "confidence": "medium"
  },
  {
    "page": 5,
    "block_id": "page_005:block_052",
    "block_type": "text",
    "text": "• For V-SZZ , it identifies vulnerability-inducing commits by treating every deleted line in the fix commit as vulnerable and tracing them back using the git blame command, aided by an AST-based line mapping to handle refactorings. In this case, it incorrectly attributes the commit e96c8f8 (corresponding to version 1.362) as the inducing commit. However, deeper semantic inspection reveals that the actual vulnerable logic was introduced in a descendant commit of e96c8f8 , which V-SZZ fails to reach due to it only tracing the vulnerable codes identified in the pre-patch commit, while neglecting the syntactic changes of these code during the backward tracing. Additionally, V-SZZ is unable to handle fixes that contain only added lines, rendering it ineffective in such scenarios.",
    "bbox": [
      45.827999114990234,
      195.3920440673828,
      440.1745300292969,
      304.8023986816406
    ],
    "reading_order": 52,
    "column_guess": null,
    "confidence": "medium"
  },
  {
    "page": 5,
    "block_id": "page_005:block_053",
    "block_type": "text",
    "text": "• For VERJava , on the other hand, it uses code similarity to match vulnerable code patterns across versions. While this helps to detect structurally similar code, it struggles when semantic equivalence exists without syntactic similarity, particularly when code evolves significantly across versions. As a result, it fails to recognize vulnerable logic in earlier versions, leading to false negatives.",
    "bbox": [
      45.8280029296875,
      302.98907470703125,
      440.4279479980469,
      364.577392578125
    ],
    "reading_order": 53,
    "column_guess": null,
    "confidence": "medium"
  },
  {
    "page": 5,
    "block_id": "page_005:block_054",
    "block_type": "text",
    "text": "• For LLM4SZZ , it employs a large language model to analyze commit messages and code diffs to identify bug-inducing commits. Despite its improved performance for bugs, it still fails to identify the correct vulnerability-inducing commit in this case, again misattributing e96c8f8 as the root cause. This failure highlights a key limitation: without contextual information such as CVE descriptions and a deeper understanding of both pre-fix and post-fix code, the model lacks the necessary reasoning to detect subtle security vulnerabilities. Moreover, like other SZZ-based approaches, LLM4SZZ is not equipped to perform extended historical tracing, which is often required to uncover long-lived vulnerabilities.",
    "bbox": [
      45.8280029296875,
      362.76507568359375,
      440.17462158203125,
      460.2193908691406
    ],
